'''Nagasaki Gokoku Shrine''' ({{lang-ja|長崎護国神社}}) is a [[Gokoku Shrines|Gokoku Shrine]] located in {{ill|Nagasaki|en|Nagasaki|qid=Q38234|lt=Nagasaki|1=Nagasaki}}, {{ill|Nagasaki Prefecture|en|Nagasaki Prefecture|qid=Q169376|lt=Nagasaki Prefecture|1=Nagasaki Prefecture}}, Japan.<ref>{{Cite web |title=長崎で「護国神社の庭フェス」 徒歩来場者には特典も |url=https://nagasaki.keizai.biz/headline/1405/ |access-date=2023-01-09 |website=長崎経済新聞}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=長崎県護国神社 {{!}} {{!}} ながさきの平和【公式】 |url=https://nagasakipeace.jp/gokoku.html |access-date=2023-01-09 |website=ながさきの平和 |language=ja}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite book |last=Chinnock |first=FRank W. |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=z01FEAAAQBAJ&dq=Nagasaki+Gokoku&pg=PT134 |title=Nagasaki: The Forgotten Bomb |date=2021-11-21 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-000-45899-2 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Sturgeon |first=William Daniel |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zHC6f08Qi5sC&dq=Nagasaki+Gokoku&pg=PA100 |title=Japan's Yasukuni Shrine: Place of Peace Or Place of Conflict? Regional Politics of History and Memory in East Asia |date=2006 |publisher=Universal-Publishers |isbn=978-1-58112-334-0 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Sturgeon |first=William Daniel |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zHC6f08Qi5sC&dq=nagasaki+gokoku+shrine&pg=PA100 |title=Japan's Yasukuni Shrine: Place of Peace Or Place of Conflict? Regional Politics of History and Memory in East Asia |date=2006 |publisher=Universal-Publishers |isbn=978-1-58112-334-0 |language=en}}</ref> It is dedicated to the spirits of the approximately 60,000 people from Nagasaki Prefecture who died between the [[Meiji Restoration]] and {{ill|Pacific War|en|Pacific War|qid=Q184425|lt=Pacific War|1=Pacific War}} (World War II).

It is dedicated to war dead. Such shrines were made to serve to enshrine the casualties of wars, and they were all considered "branches" of {{ill|Yasukuni Shrine|en|Yasukuni Shrine|qid=Q242803|lt=Yasukuni Shrine|1=Yasukuni Shrine}}. They were renamed from {{ill|Shōkonsha|en|Shōkonsha|qid=Q11497810|lt=Shokonsha|1=Shōkonsha}} in 1939.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=TAKAYAMA |first=K. PETER |date=1990 |title=Enshrinement and Persistency of Japanese Religion |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/23917081 |journal=Journal of Church and State |volume=32 |issue=3 |pages=527–547 |doi=10.1093/jcs/32.3.527 |jstor=23917081 |issn=0021-969X}}</ref>

== History ==
[[File:Nagasaki Shokon sha.jpg|thumb|Nagasaki Shokonsha. This photo depicts the old shrine, and it was completely destroyed in the atomic bombing]]
The shrine was founded in 1869 in the Umegasaki district of Nagasaki as the Nagasaki [[Gokoku Shrines|Shokonsha]], dedicated to the 43 samurais who died in the {{ill|Boshin War|en|Boshin War|qid=Q309184|lt=Boshin War|1=Boshin War}}. In 1874, the Saku Shokon Shrine was established in the Nishi-shima district of Nagasaki to honor the 536 people who died in the {{ill|Japanese invasion of Taiwan (1874)|en|Japanese invasion of Taiwan (1874)|qid=Q703942|lt=Taiwan Expedition|1=Japanese invasion of Taiwan (1874)}}. Both shrines merged and became the Nagasaki Gokoku Shrine in 1942, with the shrine buildings being completed in 1944. Then in August 1945, all of the shrine's buildings were destroyed in the {{ill|Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|en|Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki|qid=Q488|lt=atomic bombing of Nagasaki|1=Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki}}.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Hiroshima Gokoku Shrine - Hiroshima - TracesOfWar.com |url=https://www.tracesofwar.com/sights/91240/Hiroshima-Gokoku-Shrine.htm |access-date=2023-11-10 |website=www.tracesofwar.com |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":0" />{{Rp|page=121}} The Sako Shokon Shrine (Umegasaki Tenno-miya Shrine) was temporarily located at the site of the former Sako Shokonsha. It was rebuilt in October 1963. It is designated as a National Important Cultural Property. The shrine's annual festivals are held on April 22 and October 26.

